  "Title": "Installed Renewable Energy Capacity by Federal State",
  "Description": "Renewable energy production is naturally inconsistent; for instance, a dry year can significantly reduce hydropower output. Because of these fluctuations, installed capacity serves as a more stable metric for evaluating the renewable energy infrastructure across different regions.\n\n**The Leaderboard (2024)**\n\nThe distribution of installed capacity varies significantly across the federal states:\n\nLower Austria (Niederösterreich): Remains the undisputed leader in total capacity.\n\nUpper Austria (Oberösterreich): Claimed the second-place spot in 2024, overtaking Tyrol.\n\nTyrol (Tirol): Now holds the third position.\n\n**The \"Size\" Factor**\n\nThere is a clear correlation between a state's physical size and its capacity. Smaller states like Vienna, Burgenland, and Salzburg record the lowest shares. This isn't necessarily a lack of effort—smaller land areas simply offer less space for large-scale renewable installations compared to their sprawling neighbors.\n\nThis information has been published initially on https://www.energie.gv.at\nRenewable energy output in the federal states in MW in 2024, source: EAG Monitoring Report 2025 by E-Control via energie.gv.at, accessed on: February 26, 2026, 10:27 a.m.",
